{"add":{"doc":{"id":"07e48fc71f2f54ccd05031091d9cd9d2e6b9ad4b7bf2fd81c03c9d843f90d475","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Linkin_Park_%40_Sonisphere.jpg/275px-Linkin_Park_%40_Sonisphere.jpg","previous":["Alternative metal emerged from the hardcore scene of alternative rock in the US in the later 1980s, but gained a wider audience after grunge broke into the mainstream in the early 1990s.[249] Early alternative metal bands mixed a wide variety of genres with hardcore and heavy metal sensibilities, with acts like Jane's Addiction and Primus utilizing prog-rock, Soundgarden and Corrosion of Conformity using garage punk, the Jesus Lizard and Helmet mixing noise-rock, Ministry and Nine Inch Nails influenced by industrial music, Monster Magnet moving into psychedelia, Pantera, Sepultura and White Zombie creating groove metal, while Biohazard and Faith No More turned to hip hop and rap.[249]"],"after":["Hip hop had gained attention from rock acts in the early 1980s, including The Clash with \"The Magnificent Seven\" (1981) and Blondie with \"Rapture\" (1981).[250][251] Early crossover acts included Run DMC and the Beastie Boys.[252] Detroit rapper Esham became known for his \"acid rap\" style, which fused rapping with a sound that was often based in rock and heavy metal.[253][254] Rappers who sampled rock songs included Ice-T, The Fat Boys, LL Cool J, Public Enemy and Whodini.[255] The mixing of thrash metal and rap was pioneered by Anthrax on their 1987 comedy-influenced single \"I'm the Man\".[255]"]}}}